why: Primary baseline: in-kind DD effect on total per-capita expenditure with village controls (diconsa + month FEs) clustered at village level
Primary baseline for cash treatment arm: same regression as G1 but coefficient of interest is cash_fu
Decomposition of total expenditure into food component -- directly tests where the in-kind effect comes from
Decomposition of total expenditure into non-food component -- tests whether in-kind transfers crowd out non-food spending
Core mechanism test: in-kind basket goods expenditure -- strongest and most robust result (p<0.001)
Core mechanism test: non-in-kind food expenditure -- tests crowd-out of other food items (coef near zero)
Disaggregated food item: fruits and vegetables -- granular decomposition beyond the main food/nonfood/inkind split
Disaggregated food item: grains -- granular decomposition of food expenditure
Disaggregated food item: pulses -- individual food category effect
Disaggregated food item: meat -- individual food category effect
Disaggregated food item: dairy -- individual food category effect
Disaggregated food item: cooking fat -- individual food category effect
Disaggregated food item: junk food -- individual food category effect
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: corn flour -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: rice -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: beans -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: powdered milk -- largest item-level effect (coef=23.44 p<0.001)
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: oil -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: canned fish -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: cookies -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: pasta -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: cereal -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated in-kind basket item: lentils -- one of 10 basket items
Disaggregated non-food: schooling expenditure -- granular nonfood decomposition
Disaggregated non-food: clothing expenditure -- granular nonfood decomposition
Disaggregated non-food: medical/hygiene expenditure -- granular nonfood decomposition
Disaggregated non-food: household items expenditure -- granular nonfood decomposition
No village-level controls -- tests sensitivity to control inclusion (coef=55.63 p=0.015)
Adds household size control to baseline village controls
Adds demographic controls (age/education of head etc.) to baseline village controls
Adds housing quality controls to baseline village controls
Full set of baseline household controls -- most complete control specification (coef=53.53 p=0.026)
Leave-one-out: drop Diconsa store indicator from village controls
Leave-one-out: drop month-of-interview FE for month 3
Leave-one-out: drop month-of-interview FE for month 10
Leave-one-out: drop month-of-interview FE for month 11
Leave-one-out: drop month-of-interview FE for month 12
Excludes in-kind without education group -- tests sensitivity to pooling assumption
Only in-kind+education vs cash (drops in-kind without education) -- identical to exclude_ik_no_educ
Restricts sample to states with balanced treatment assignment
Restricts to households with children -- tests whether effect depends on household composition
Restricts to households without children
Restricts to large households (above median size)
Restricts to small households (below median size)
Restricts to farming households
Restricts to non-farming households
Restricts to indigenous households
Restricts to non-indigenous households
Restricts to villages with Diconsa store
Restricts to villages without Diconsa store
Heteroskedasticity-robust SEs instead of village-clustered -- same point estimate different inference
SEs clustered at municipality level instead of village level
SEs clustered at state level instead of village level -- fewer clusters but broader
Log transformation of total expenditure -- tests proportional effects (coef=0.141 p=0.003)
Inverse hyperbolic sine transformation -- robust to zeros while approximating log
Total household expenditure in levels (not per capita) -- tests per-capita normalization
Per adult-equivalent expenditure instead of per-capita -- alternative normalization
Heterogeneity: households with low education head -- subgroup decomposition
Heterogeneity: households with high education head -- subgroup decomposition
Heterogeneity: below-median baseline expenditure households
Heterogeneity: above-median baseline expenditure households
Heterogeneity: male-headed households
Heterogeneity: female-headed households
Placebo: baseline cross-sectional difference in total expenditure between in-kind and control (treatment var is ik not ik_fu) -- should be zero under random assignment
Placebo: baseline cross-sectional difference in food expenditure -- tests pre-treatment balance
Placebo: baseline cross-sectional difference in non-food expenditure -- tests pre-treatment balance
Placebo-like: DD effect on schooling expenditure -- should not be affected by food transfers
Placebo-like: DD effect on household items expenditure -- should not be affected by food transfers
Cash treatment effect on food expenditure -- different treatment variable (cash_fu)
Cash treatment effect on non-food expenditure -- different treatment variable
Cash treatment effect on in-kind basket goods -- tests whether cash also increases basket items
Cash treatment effect on non-in-kind food -- tests composition difference between cash and in-kind
Household fixed effects instead of village controls -- absorbs all time-invariant HH heterogeneity (coef=52.44 p=0.018)
Household FE with food expenditure outcome -- HH FE version of food decomposition
Household FE with in-kind basket goods outcome -- HH FE version of mechanism test
Winsorize total expenditure at 1st/99th percentile -- tests sensitivity to outliers
Winsorize total expenditure at 5th/95th percentile -- more aggressive outlier trimming
